Weather and CitiBike Data Findings

Patrick Lucey

SQL Queries used for analysis

WITH seasonal_data AS (
    SELECT 
        EXTRACT(YEAR FROM starttime) as year,
        CASE 
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (12,1,2) THEN 'Winter'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (3,4,5) THEN 'Spring'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (6,7,8) THEN 'Summer'
            ELSE 'Fall'
        END as season,
        COUNT(*) as trip_count,
        AVG(tripduration_min) as avg_duration,
        AVG(cpw_temperature) as avg_temp
    FROM citi_weather
    GROUP BY 
        EXTRACT(YEAR FROM starttime),
        CASE 
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (12,1,2) THEN 'Winter'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (3,4,5) THEN 'Spring'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (6,7,8) THEN 'Summer'
            ELSE 'Fall'
        END
)
SELECT * FROM seasonal_data
ORDER BY year, season;
WITH time_periods AS (
    SELECT 
        cpw_temperature,
        usertype,
        CASE 
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 8 THEN 'Morning (8AM)'
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 12 THEN 'Noon'
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 17 THEN 'Afternoon (5PM)'
        END as time_period,
        tripduration_min,
        starttime
    FROM citi_weather
    WHERE EXTRACT(YEAR FROM starttime) = 2019
        AND EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) BETWEEN 5 AND 8  -- Summer months (May to August)
        AND EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) IN (8, 12, 17)
        AND usertype == 'Customer'  -- Casual users
        AND tripduration_min > 5 AND tripduration_min < 200  -- Trip duration range
        AND cpw_temperature > 32  -- Temperature above 32°C (89.6°F)
)
SELECT 
    usertype,
    time_period,
    EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) as month,
    tripduration_min,
    cpw_temperature
FROM time_periods
ORDER BY 
    month,
    time_period;

Seasonal Pattern visual analysis

# Seasonal Patterns
ggplot(season_type_data, aes(x=year, y=trip_count, fill=season)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge") +
  #geom_smooth(aes(group=season), method="lm", se=FALSE) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set3") +
  labs(title="Seasonal Usage Patterns Over Years 2013-2019",
       x="Year",
       y="Number of Trips") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))

In this plot, we can see that the number of trips taken by users of the bike-sharing service has increased over the years. The number of trips taken in the summer months is higher than in the other seasons. The number of trips taken in the winter months is the lowest. This pattern is consistent across all years from 2013 to 2019. This pattern led me to want to examine the relationship between the temperature and the duration of trips taken by users in different weather conditions. I wanted to focus on the extreme weather conditions, so I decided to analyze the relationship between temperature and trip duration in temperatures above 32°C (89.6°F) and below -6°C (20°F). Another decison that was influenced by this grpah was to focus on the year 2019 for the regression. As to the fact that this year had the most data points within my collected data set. Also, another finding from this plot is that the number of trips in each year seems to be continuously increasing. Which could be attributed to the fact that the CitiBike service is becoming more popular over the years, and including more stations throughout the 5 boroughs.

Spline Regression Model

# Create a spline regression model for temperatures over 32°C
model_s <- lm(tripduration_min ~ ns(cpw_temperature, 
                                   knots = 1) + 
                                   factor(time_period), 
              data = spline_temp_90)
modelsummary(model_s,
  title = "Spline Regression Results: Temperature Impact on Trip Duration",
  stars = TRUE,                     # Add significance stars
  gof_map = c("nobs", "r.squared", "adj.r.squared"), # Show key statistics
  fmt = 2,                         # Round to 2 decimal places
  output = "kableExtra") %>%       # Use kableExtra formatting
  kableExtra::kable_styling(
    bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"),
    full_width = FALSE,
    position = "center"
  )

Model validation

# Create diagnostic plots
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model_s)


# Calculate AIC and BIC
AIC(model_s)
## [1] 123700.9
BIC(model_s)
## [1] 123731.1

Analysis and validation of Summertime Spline Regression Model

Based upon the results from the spline regression with temperatures above 32°C, we can see that the model is statistically significant with a P-Value of near 0. Which means that the model can be used for analysis. However the R-squared value is only .003. Which means that the model explains 0.03% of the variance in trip duration. The AIC and BIC values are 123700 and 123731, respectively. This indicates that the model is not a good fit for the data. The diagnostic plots show that the residuals are not normally distributed and that there is heteroscedasticity in the model. This suggests that the model is not a good fit for the data and that there are other factors that are influencing trip duration in temperatures above 32°C.

Conclusion and Future Work

Perhaps in future analysis, we could include other variables such as humidity, wind speed, and precipitation to see if they have an effect on trip duration in extreme weather conditions. We could also look at other time periods to see if there are any patterns in trip duration during different times of the day. This could help us to better understand the relationship between temperature and trip duration and to identify any factors that may be influencing trip duration in extreme weather conditions. Also, another possibility among unsubscribing customers is that they might be using the service for leisure purposes, and not for commuting. This could be a reason why the trip duration is not affected by the temperature. Also, due to the nature of Manhattan riding a bike on very hot day may be more comfortable than riding the subway or walking. As to the fact that while riding a bike it can generate a much needed breeze on a hot summer day.
